Surface modification by laser irradiation is in the core of many modern processing and fabrication techniques, including laser surface alloying, annealing, hardening, and amorphization.  The ability of short pulse laser irradiation to produce unique surface morphologies, metastable phases and microstructure (arrangement of crystal defects) has been demonstrated in numerous studies and is generally attributed to the conditions of strong electronic, thermal, phase, and mechanical non-equilibrium created in irradiated targets by the fast laser excitation.  Detailed understanding of the relations between the basic mechanisms of laser interaction with materials, non-equilibrium processes caused by the fast deposition of laser energy, and the resulting microstructure and properties of laser-treated regions of the targets, however, is still lacking, thus limiting the expansion of laser technologies into the new domain of nanoscale material processing and fabrication.

In the NSF-sponsored research, Professor Zhigilei and his team at the University of Virginia are developing advanced computational tools for simulation of laser interactions with materials and apply these tools for detailed analysis of the mechanisms of mass transport, phase transformations, and microstructure development under highly non-equilibrium conditions created by the fast laser energy deposition.  Several examples of research finding in this project are illustrated in the images included with this report and are listed below.

(1) prediction of nanocrystalline structure of nanoscale surface features generated by highly localized excitation of a thin metal film [J. Appl. Phys. 107, 013519, 2010];

(2) explanation of a surprising observation of laser melting of nanocrystalline metals at temperatures below the equilibrium melting temperature [J. Phys. Chem. C 114, 5686, 2010];

(3) analysis of the complex three-dimensional corrugated structure of lattice-mismatched interface generated in laser processing of Cu-Ag layered target [Appl. Phys. A 104, 781, 2011];

(4) explanation of the origins of experimentally observed bimodal nanoparticle size distribution in laser ablation of thin films [Appl. Phys. Lett. 104, 193106, 2014];

(5) establishment of links between the microscopic mechanisms of laser ablation of metal targets and the parameters of the ejected plume [Appl. Phys. A 114, 11, 2014];

(6) elucidation of distinct characteristics of laser interactions with a metal target under conditions of spatial confinement by a solid transparent overlayer [J. Appl. Phys. 115, 183501, 2014];

(7) establishment of a "processing map" exposing the range of parameters suitable for the ejection of intact biomolecules in matrix-assisted pulsed laser evaporation (MAPLE) with smallest possible amount of "matrix" [J. Phys. Chem. B 118, 13290, 2014];

(8) prediction of the generation of sub-surface voids and nanocrystalline surface layer with random crystallographic orientation of nanograins and a high density of stacking faults, twins, and nanoscale twinned structural elements with five-fold symmetry [Phys. Rev. B 91, 035413, 2015].

The results obtained within this program are reported in 17 invited and 26 contributed presentations, 16 publications, 1 Ph.D. thesis, and one undergraduate thesis.

The broader impact of this program is in the implications of the physical insights revealed in this project for the advancement of laser applications based on controlled surface modification at the nanoscale and the development of new experimental techniques for generation of surface structures with unusual non-equilibrium structures and compositions.  At the educational front, the project has provided training and multidisciplinary research experience to three graduate students, three undergraduate students, and a high-school teacher participating in this project with support of the NSF Summer Research Experience for Teachers program.  Most students supported by this grant were trained i...
